SIMPLE: majesty
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Majesty
<hw>Maj"es*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Majesties</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>magestee</ets>,
F. <ets>majest⟦eacute⟧</ets>, L. <ets>majestas</ets>, fr. an old compar.
of <ets>magnus</ets> great. See <er>Major</er>, <er>Master</er>.]</ety>
<def>The dignity and authority of sovereign power; quality or state
which inspires awe or reverence; grandeur; exalted dignity, whether
proceeding from rank, character, or bearing; imposing loftiness;
stateliness; -- usually applied to the rank and dignity of
sovereigns.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord reigneth; he is clothed with <qex>majesty</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. xciii. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No sovereign has ever represented the <qex>majesty</qex> of a
great state with more dignity and grace.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, used with the possessive pronoun, the title
of an emperor, king or queen; -- in this sense taking a plural; <as>as,
their <ex>majesties</ex> attended the concert</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In all the public writs which he [Emperor Charles V.] now issued
as King of Spain, he assumed the title of <qex>Majesty</qex>, and
required it from his subjects as a mark of respect. Before that time all
the monarchs of Europe were satisfied with the appellation of
<qex>Highness</qex> or <qex>Grace</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Robertson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Dignity; elevation of manner or style.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Majidae</ent>⟦br⟧
